Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, this week I introduced a bill which if enacted I truly believe will be much to improve conditions in the automobile industry.

18:40.000 --> 18:50.000
I was joined in this bill by Senator Langer of North Dakota, Senator Douglas of Illinois, Senator O'Malley of Wyoming, Senator Hinnings of Missouri, and Senator Carol of Colorado.

18:50.000 --> 19:06.000
It is an excise cut with a difference however. The present excise tax on automobiles is 10%. My bill proposes that this tax remain in force, but that the manufacturer may receive a credit of one half of his tax obligation.

19:06.000 --> 19:13.000
If he refunds the amount of such a credit to the ultimate retail buyer of his products, that is of the automobile.

19:13.000 --> 19:19.000
The buyer of the new automobile would receive this refund as a lump sum payment directly from the manufacturer.

19:19.000 --> 19:25.000
In this way there could be no possibility of his not getting the benefit of the tax reduction.

19:25.000 --> 19:32.000
The bill has another important feature. It would make any such reduction retroactive to May 1, 1958.

19:33.000 --> 19:43.000
I believe that this is very essential. During my, during discussion of my proposal or any other, sometimes will have to be taken.

19:43.000 --> 19:49.000
During this time prospective buyers of automobiles may be uncertain as to the course congress may take.

19:49.000 --> 19:58.000
They therefore might be tempted to wait to buy and to wait on buying an automobile and to hope that a reduction of tax is going to take place.

19:59.000 --> 20:12.000
But what we are telling them is buy now and because the tax is retroactive, you can be assured that you will receive the benefit of any changes in the tax or any reduction in the tax which congress may enact.

