29:47.000 --> 29:56.000
The price line, unless something is done to stop it, is soon going to run off the charts. I've been trying to call attention to this very dangerous situation while there is still time.

29:57.000 --> 30:08.000
Although my efforts long predate this, I have made a public speech about it on the floor of the United States Senate. Every day since June 13th and I shall continue to do so, every day until July 1st.

30:08.000 --> 30:23.000
Nevertheless, I want to say that this is a rather lonely road to travel. I never met anyone else on the road. Everyone from the present down complains about inflation, housewives, businessmen, laborers, farmers. All make noise about how horrible inflation is.

30:23.000 --> 30:31.000
At the never-lift of finger while the horse is walking out of the barn door. They just hope apparently that someone will close the door after he is gone.

30:31.000 --> 30:39.000
Well, the door is wide open now and the horse is standing there, sniffing the fresh breeze and about ready to take off at a gulla.

30:39.000 --> 30:50.000
July 1st will be too late. On that date, there will be an automatic increase in the steel workers' wages under the three-year contract which the United Steel Workers signed with the steel company.

30:50.000 --> 31:03.000
And based on all of the evidence of the past, the steel companies will then raise their prices by at least twice the amount of the wage increase. This was what they did in 1957 and seemed to have done every year.

31:03.000 --> 31:17.000
Well, once steel is up, everything else is going to take another rise. Automobiles will go up, ranges, refrigerators, TV, sets, freezers. All of them use steel and all of them will go up.

31:17.000 --> 31:30.000
The tin can industry has already started hinting that they will have to increase the price of their cans. That means that when you go to the grocery store, you will find another penny marked on the can goods items, the extra cost of the can.

31:30.000 --> 31:40.000
The Senate this week has been working on the tax bill and there has been much discussion of reducing excess taxes by various amounts in order to decrease the cost of goods.

31:40.000 --> 31:56.000
And I supported some of these myself, but I can tell you that the Senate is spinning its wheels by going down that road. Because another steel price rise would set off another round of general price increases that would quickly gobble up any excess tax decrease.

31:56.000 --> 32:04.000
On May 27th, I wrote President Eisenhower about this situation, setting out a program to stop the price increase by voluntary methods.

32:04.000 --> 32:10.000
On June 3rd, he wrote me saying an effect that he thought it best to follow the program on which he had already embarked.

32:10.000 --> 32:16.000
Well, I do not know exactly what his program is in this regard, but I do know that it hasn't worked so far.

32:16.000 --> 32:25.000
I know also that the voluntary program which I outlined to the President has worked in the past, and I am convinced that it would work again. It's really simple enough.

32:25.000 --> 32:35.000
The President would appeal directly to the heads of the steel industry and to the heads of the steel union as patriotic citizens to stop this terrible inflationary move.

32:35.000 --> 32:44.000
He has the authority not only to do this, but to require information from them as to cost, productivity, and so on, and to make that public.

32:44.000 --> 33:00.000
If the appeal to good citizenship didn't work, then I think publicity would. For labor is certainly sensitive to public opinion at this time, and even the companies know that they have to live with the public and sell their products to the public, and so they are not insensitive either.

33:00.000 --> 33:04.000
If you don't think this system would work, then I would like for you to look at history.

33:04.000 --> 33:15.000
The Four World War One things we are going about like we are now. And between July 1914 and November 1916, the price of steel rose 103%.

33:15.000 --> 33:27.000
During a 28-month comparable period between August 1939 and December 1941, when a voluntary system to this was an effect that I have been talking about, it advanced only 2%.

33:27.000 --> 33:38.000
Other comparisons are just as impressive, but July 1st will be too late to make this move. By then the price of steel will be up, the inflationary aspire will run through all industry.

33:38.000 --> 33:52.000
And very soon thereafter, after our predict, there will be more unemployment and a little bit bigger recession. It's also unnecessary. It could all be prevented if we would only act now. Thank you and goodbye until next week.

